Gnome sees ogre.<br>
Gnome runs away, screaming in terror and escapes the probability of gnomebashing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Why would the gnome run away if the game mechanics prevent the ogre from hurting him in the first place?<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Ogre sees gnome.<br>
Gnome sees ogre.<br>
Ogre sees full party of well-equipped bodyguards with said gnome, decides discretion is the better part of valor (or a rumbling tummy), and finds a nearby bear to maul instead.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again this would assume the reason the ogre does not attack the gnome is because he has a high chance of losing, not because the game prevents him from doing so.  <br>
<br>
Yes PvP and RP are not the same thing, but they are not opposed to one another by any means.  Paladins and Shadow Knights, Druids and Necromancers, Dark elves and High elves, there are just some situations in which PvP does make sence.  Of course there are situations in which PvP is not a sensable solution but there are also those where it is.  My argument would be that lack of PvP prevents roleplaying solutions to situations rather than encouraging them, how else would you suggest a group of elves stop a PoG raid by an evil guild? <p><B>Vachir</B><BR>
